<section class="copy">
    <p>Family-owned businesses account for more than <a href="https://unctad.org/news/empowering-family-businesses-fast-track-sustainable-development" target="_blank">70 per cent</a> of global GDP, yet many of those are poorly prepared for succession. As wealth moves from founders to their children – and sometimes grandchildren – tensions often arise around strategy, sustainability and shared leadership. According to an <a href="https://www.ey.com/en_us/insights/family-enterprise/why-family-offices-need-refreshed-operating-models" target="_blank">EY survey</a>, just 40 per cent of family-run companies have a formal succession plan in place, and even fewer have addressed how that plan should evolve as the business and family grow.</p>
    <p>“When we look at sources of conflict in family systems, tradition versus innovation is a pretty classic one,” says Peter Vogel, Professor of Family Business and Entrepreneurship at IMD Business School. “Do we hold on to this business unit or not? Do we continue running this product even though it’s not profitable? There might be a reluctance to change, especially when the legacy of earlier generations is involved.”</p>
    <p>María Eugenia Mosquera, Head of Wealth Planning, Key Clients and Family Office Services at Julius Baer, a global wealth management company, agrees that there can be generational differences in vision and values that cause family conflict if not addressed early. “If there’s also a lack of a formal governance structure, then this becomes exacerbated,” she says. “Often this means there is no effective conflict resolution mechanism, an informal decision-making process and a delayed or non-transparent process in ownership succession planning.”</p>
</section>

