<section class="copy">
    <h2>The power of diverse perspectives</h2>
    <p>When handled well, however, generational diversity can be a strength. Research suggests that younger members of family boards are more likely to champion sustainability, employee wellbeing and digital innovation. A <a href="https://www.pwc.com/gx/en/news-room/press-releases/2022/global-next-gen-survey-2022.html" target="_blank">PWC Next Gen survey</a> reveals that ESG initiatives can be accelerated by younger voices who are less beholden to legacy models. An <a href="https://www.imd.org/ibyimd/family-business/redefining-wealth-management-how-family-offices-can-lead-the-charge-in-responsible-investing-2/" target="_blank">IMD paper</a>, written by Vogel, supports this, suggesting that family offices are uniquely positioned to lead the charge in responsible investing – if empowered to act decisively.</p>
    <p>For Mosquera, creating space for different voices is essential. “Multigenerational boards are incredibly rich in terms of diversity of thought,” she says. “But that only works if we create environments where everyone is heard and valued.”</p>
    <p>That includes women. In regions with strong patriarchal cultures, female successors often face additional barriers. “It’s not just about family dynamics, but societal ones,” says Vogel. “In Asia or the Middle East, even the sons can struggle to challenge elders, let alone daughters.” Yet family businesses that take what <a href="https://kpmg.com/nz/en/home/insights/2024/06/global-family-business-survey.html" target="_blank">a KPMG study</a> calls a “dynamic” approach to legacy report stronger business performance compared to competitors.</p>
</section>

